    <h1>Foods That Are Dangerous for Cats: A Comprehensive Guide</h1>
    <p>Cats are often curious and adventurous eaters, but not all foods are safe for them. <br>
        We aim to educate cat owners about which foods to avoid to keep their feline companions healthy and happy.<br>
         Here’s a detailed guide to help you understand what’s harmful and why.</p>

        > <h1> TOXIC FOODS TO AVOID</h1>
        <h3>CHOCOLATE</h3>
        <img src="https://tse1.mm.bing.net/th/id/OIP.Ef84_vxHZD3m_AaZlLc27gAAAA?w=295&h=197&c=7&r=0&o=5&pid=1.7 " width="300"/>
<p> Why It’s Dangerous: Contains theobromine and caffeine, which can cause vomiting, diarrhea, rapid breathing, and seizures.<br>
    Symptoms of Toxicity: Vomiting, diarrhea, rapid heartbeat, tremors, seizures. <br>
    Emergency Action: Contact your vet immediately if you suspect your cat has ingested chocolate. </p>

    <h1>Onions and Garlic   </h1>
    <img src="https://tse1.mm.bing.net/th/id/OIP.pZ6dPhfSfrLdI0u_NcprDQAAAA?w=203&h=144&c=7&r=0&o=5&pid=1.7 " width="300"/>

    <p> Why It’s Dangerous: Contains compounds that can cause oxidative damage to red blood cells, leading to hemolytic anemia.<br>
        Symptoms of Toxicity: Weakness, lethargy, pale gums, and a decrease in appetite.<br>
        Emergency Action: Seek veterinary help if you notice any signs of lethargy or if you know your cat has consumed these foods.  </p>
 
        <h1> Grapes and Raisins </h1>
        <img src=" https://tse3.mm.bing.net/th/id/OIP.4aWJAtQ_a6Y76exaJuySCAHaEe?w=275&h=180&c=7&r=0&o=5&pid=1.7" width="300" />
        <p>Why It’s Dangerous: Can cause acute kidney failure in cats, though the exact toxin is not yet identified.<br>
            Symptoms of Toxicity: Vomiting, diarrhea, lethargy, loss of appetite.<br>
            Emergency Action: Contact your veterinarian immediately for advice and possible treatment. </p>

            <h1> Alcohol </h1>
            
            <p> Why It’s Dangerous: Can lead to alcohol poisoning, affecting the central nervous system and causing vomiting, difficulty breathing, and potentially coma.<br>
                Symptoms of Toxicity: Vomiting, disorientation, tremors, and unsteady gait.<br>
                Emergency Action: Get in touch with your vet right away if you suspect alcohol consumption.</p>
 
                <h1> Dairy Products </h1>
                <img src=" https://tse1.mm.bing.net/th/id/OIP.JfV5_T4y4KPn62OdvcXPGwHaE6?w=243&h=180&c=7&r=0&o=5&pid=1.7 " width="300"/>
                <p> Why It’s Dangerous: Many cats are lactose intolerant and can’t digest lactose properly, leading to gastrointestinal upset.<br>
                    Symptoms of Toxicity: Diarrhea, vomiting, and abdominal discomfort.<br>
                    Emergency Action: Monitor your cat’s reaction and consult your vet if symptoms persist. </p>
            </body>
